[src:flame-graphs/call-graph] A **call graph** (also known as a **call multigraph**) is a control-flow graph, which represents calling relationships between subroutines in a computer program.
[src:flame-graphs/call-graph] Each node represents a procedure and each edge *(f, g)* indicates that procedure *f* calls procedure *g*.
[src:flame-graphs/call-graph] Thus, a cycle in the graph indicates recursive procedure calls.
[src:flame-graphs/call-graph] A dynamic call graph is a record of an execution of the program, for example as output by a profiler.
[src:flame-graphs/call-graph] Thus, a dynamic call graph can be exact, but only describes one run of the program.
[src:flame-graphs/call-graph] A static call graph is a call graph intended to represent every possible run of the program.
[src:flame-graphs/call-graph] The exact static call graph is an undecidable problem, so static call graph algorithms are generally overapproximations.
[src:flame-graphs/call-graph] That is, every call relationship that occurs is represented in the graph, and possibly also some call relationships that would never occur in actual runs of the program.
[src:flame-graphs/call-graph] Call graphs can be defined to represent varying degrees of precision.
[src:flame-graphs/call-graph] A more precise call graph more precisely approximates the behavior of the real program, at the cost of taking longer to compute and more memory to store.
[src:flame-graphs/call-graph] The most precise call graph is fully *context-sensitive*, which means that for each procedure, the graph contains a separate node for each call stack that procedure can be activated with.
[src:flame-graphs/call-graph] A fully context-sensitive call graph is called a calling context tree.
[src:flame-graphs/call-graph] This can be computed dynamically easily, although it may take up a large amount of memory.
[src:flame-graphs/call-graph] Calling context trees are usually not computed statically, because it would take too long for a large program.
[src:flame-graphs/call-graph] The least precise call graph is *context-insensitive*, which means that there is only one node for each procedure.
[src:flame-graphs/call-graph] With languages that feature dynamic dispatch (e.g.
[src:flame-graphs/call-graph] Java or C++), first-class functions (e.g.
[src:flame-graphs/call-graph] Python or Racket), or function pointers (e.g.
[src:flame-graphs/call-graph] C), computing a static call graph precisely requires alias analysis results.
[src:flame-graphs/call-graph] Conversely, computing precise aliasing requires a call graph.
[src:flame-graphs/call-graph] Many static analysis systems solve the apparent infinite regress by computing both simultaneously.
[src:flame-graphs/call-graph] Call graphs can be used in different ways.
[src:flame-graphs/call-graph] One simple application of call graphs is finding procedures that are never called.
[src:flame-graphs/call-graph] Call graphs can act as documentation for humans to understand programs.
[src:flame-graphs/call-graph] Call graphs can also be used to detect anomalies of program execution or code injection attacks.
[src:flame-graphs/call-graph] Static and dynamic analysis engines for both host and embedded software, with a myriad of reports including call graphs.
[src:flame-graphs/call-graph] Turns a text representation of any graph (including a call graph) into a picture.
[src:flame-graphs/call-graph] Command-line utility that performs a topological sort.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] In computer science, a **call stack** is a stack data structure that stores information about the active subroutines and inline blocks of a computer program.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] This type of stack is also known as an **execution stack**, **program stack**, **control stack**, **run-time stack**, or **machine stack**, and is often shortened to simply the "**stack**".
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Although maintenance of the call stack is important for the proper functioning of most software, the details are normally hidden and automatic in high-level programming languages.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Many computer instruction sets provide special instructions for manipulating stacks.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] A call stack is used for several related purposes, but the main reason for having one is to keep track of the point to which each active subroutine should return control when it finishes executing.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] An active subroutine is one that has been called, but is yet to complete execution, after which control should be handed back to the point of call.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Such activations of subroutines may be nested to any level (recursive as a special case), hence the stack structure.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] For example, if a subroutine `DrawSquare` calls a subroutine `DrawLine` from four different places, `DrawLine` must know where to return when its execution completes.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] To accomplish this, the address following the instruction that jumps to `DrawLine`, the *return address*, is pushed onto the top of the call stack as part of each call.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] If a called subroutine calls on yet another subroutine, it will push another return address onto the call stack, and so on, with the information stacking up and unstacking as the program dictates.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] If the pushing consumes all of the space allocated for the call stack, an error called a stack overflow occurs, generally causing the program to crash.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Adding a block's or subroutine's entry to the call stack is sometimes called "winding", and removing entries "unwinding".
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] There is usually exactly one call stack associated with a running program (or more accurately, with each task or thread of a process), although additional stacks may be created for signal handling or cooperative multitasking (as with setcontext).
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Since there is only one in this important context, it can be referred to as *the* stack (implicitly "of the task"); however, in the Forth programming language the *data stack* or *parameter stack* is accessed more explicitly than the call stack and is commonly referred to as *the* stack (see below).
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] In high-level programming languages, the specifics of the call stack are usually hidden from the programmer.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] They are given access only to a set of functions, and not the memory on the stack itself.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Most assembly languages, on the other hand, require programmers to be involved in manipulating the stack.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] The actual details of the stack in a programming language depend upon the compiler, operating system, and the available instruction set.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] As noted above, the primary purpose of a call stack is to *store the return addresses*.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] When a subroutine is called, the location (address) of the instruction at which the calling routine can later resume must be saved somewhere.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Using a stack to save the return address has important advantages over some alternative calling conventions, such as saving the return address before the beginning of the called subroutine or in some other fixed location.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] One is that each task can have its own stack, and thus the subroutine can be thread-safe, that is, able to be active simultaneously for different tasks doing different things.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Another benefit is that by providing reentrancy, recursion is automatically supported.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] When a function calls itself recursively, a return address needs to be stored for each activation of the function so that it can later be used to return from the function activation.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Stack structures provide this capability automatically.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] , the variables that are known only within the active subroutine and do not retain values after it returns.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] It is often convenient to allocate space for this use by simply moving the top of the stack by enough to provide the space.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Note that each separate activation of a subroutine gets its own separate space in the stack for locals.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] may allocate a stack frame for local variables.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] As with a call frame, the values are lost when the block exits.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] be supplied to them by the code which calls them, and it is not uncommon that space for these parameters may be laid out in the call stack.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] will be used to pass the values, but if there are more parameters than can be handled this way, memory space will be needed.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] The call stack works well as a place for these parameters, especially since each call to a subroutine, which will have differing values for parameters, will be given separate space on the call stack for those values.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Operands for arithmetic or logical operations are most often placed into registers and operated on there.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] , is called an evaluation stack, and may occupy space in the call stack.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] , which are allowed to access the context of their enclosing routines, i.e., the parameters and local variables within the scope of the outer routines.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Such static nesting can repeat (a function declared within a function declared within a function…).
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] The implementation must provide a means by which a called function at any given static nesting level can reference the enclosing frame at each enclosing nesting level.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] which is indexed to locate a desired frame.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] The depth of a routine's lexical nesting is a known constant, so the size of a routine's display is fixed.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Also, the number of containing scopes to traverse is known, the index into the display is also fixed.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] implemented such a display in hardware which supported up to 32 levels of static nesting.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] The display entries denoting containing scopes are obtained from the appropriate prefix of the caller's display.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] An inner routine which recurses creates separate call frames for each invocation.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] In this case, all of the inner routine's static links point to the same outer routine context.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] , a block within a procedure may have its own local variables, allocated on block entry and freed on block exit.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Similarly, the block may have its own exception handlers, deactivated at block exit.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Beside the return address, in some environments there may be other machine or software states that need to be restored when a subroutine returns.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] This might include things like privilege level, exception-handling information, arithmetic modes, and so on.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] If needed, this may be stored in the call stack just as the return address is.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] The typical call stack is used for the return address, locals, and parameters (known as a *call frame*).
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] In some environments there may be more or fewer functions assigned to the call stack.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Some Forths also have a third stack for floating-point parameters.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] A call stack is composed of **stack frames** (also called *activation records* or *activation frames*).
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] These are machine dependent and ABI-dependent data structures containing subroutine state information.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Each stack frame corresponds to an invocation of a subroutine that has not yet completed with a return.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] The stack frame at the top of the stack is for the currently executing routine.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] For example, if a subroutine named `DrawLine` is currently running, having been called by a subroutine `DrawSquare`, the top part of the call stack might be laid out like in the adjacent picture.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] A diagram like this can be drawn in either direction as long as the placement of the top, and so direction of stack growth, is understood.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Architectures differ as to whether call stacks grow towards higher addresses or towards lower addresses, so the logic of any diagram is not dependent on this addressing choice by convention.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] While it is actively executing, with its frame at the stack top, a routine can access the information within its frame as needed.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] When stack frame sizes can differ, such as between different functions or between invocations of a particular function, popping a frame off the stack does not constitute a fixed decrement of the **stack pointer**.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] At function return, the stack pointer is instead restored to the **frame pointer**, the value of the stack pointer just before the function was called.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Each stack frame contains a frame pointer to the top of the frame immediately below.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] The stack pointer is a mutable register shared between all invocations.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] A frame pointer of a given invocation of a function is a copy of the stack pointer as it was before the function was invoked.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] The locations of all other fields in the frame can be defined relative either to the top of the frame, as negative offsets of the stack pointer, or relative to the top of the frame below, as positive offsets of the frame pointer.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] The location of the frame pointer itself must inherently be defined as a negative offset of the stack pointer.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] In most systems a stack frame has a field to contain the previous value of the frame pointer register, the value it had while the caller was executing.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] For example, the stack frame of `DrawLine` would have a memory location holding the frame pointer value that `DrawSquare` uses (not shown in the diagram above).
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] The value is saved upon entry to the subroutine.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Having such a field in a known location in the stack frame enables code to access each frame successively underneath the currently executing routine's frame, and also allows the routine to easily restore the frame pointer to the *caller's* frame, just before it returns.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Programming languages that support nested subroutines also have a field in the call frame that points to the stack frame of the *latest* activation of the procedure that most closely encapsulates the callee, i.e. the immediate *scope* of the callee.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] This is called an *access link* or *static link* (as it keeps track of static nesting during dynamic and recursive calls) and provides the routine (as well as any other routines it may invoke) access to the local data of its encapsulating routines at every nesting level.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Some architectures, compilers, or optimization cases store one link for each enclosing level (not just the immediately enclosing), so that deeply nested routines that access shallow data do not have to traverse several links; this strategy is often called a "display".
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Access links can be optimized away when an inner function does not access any (non-constant) local data in the encapsulation, as is the case with pure functions communicating only via arguments and return values, for example.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] For some purposes, the stack frame of a subroutine and that of its caller can be considered to overlap, the overlap consisting of the area where the parameters are passed from the caller to the callee.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] In some environments, the caller pushes each argument onto the stack, thus extending its stack frame, then invokes the callee.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] In other environments, the caller has a preallocated area at the top of its stack frame to hold the arguments it supplies to other subroutines it calls.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] This area is sometimes termed the *outgoing arguments area* or *callout area*.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Under this approach, the size of the area is calculated by the compiler to be the largest needed by any called subroutine.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Usually the call stack manipulation needed at the site of a call to a subroutine is minimal (which is good since there can be many call sites for each subroutine to be called).
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] The values for the actual arguments are evaluated at the call site, since they are specific to the particular call, and either pushed onto the stack or placed into registers, as determined by the used calling convention.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] The actual call instruction, such as "branch and link", is then typically executed to transfer control to the code of the target subroutine.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] In the called subroutine, the first code executed is usually termed the subroutine prologue, since it does the necessary housekeeping before the code for the statements of the routine is begun.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Similarly, the current stack pointer and/or frame pointer values may be pushed.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] If frame pointers are being used, the prologue will typically set the new value of the frame pointer register from the stack pointer.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Space on the stack for local variables can then be allocated by incrementally changing the stack pointer.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] The Forth programming language allows explicit winding of the call stack (called there the "return stack").
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] When a subroutine is ready to return, it executes an epilogue that undoes the steps of the prologue.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] This will typically restore saved register values (such as the frame pointer value) from the stack frame, pop the entire stack frame off the stack by changing the stack pointer value, and finally branch to the instruction at the return address.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Under many calling conventions, the items popped off the stack by the epilogue include the original argument values, in which case there usually are no further stack manipulations that need to be done by the caller.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] With some calling conventions, however, it is the caller's responsibility to remove the arguments from the stack after the return.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Returning from the called function will pop the top frame off the stack, perhaps leaving a return value.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] The more general act of popping one or more frames off the stack to resume execution elsewhere in the program is called **stack unwinding** and must be performed when non-local control structures are used, such as those used for exception handling.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] In this case, the stack frame of a function contains one or more entries specifying exception handlers.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] When an exception is thrown, the stack is unwound until a handler is found that is prepared to handle (catch) the type of the thrown exception.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Some languages have other control structures that require general unwinding.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Pascal allows a global goto statement to transfer control out of a nested function and into a previously invoked outer function.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] This operation requires the stack to be unwound, removing as many stack frames as necessary to restore the proper context to transfer control to the target statement within the enclosing outer function.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Similarly, C has the `setjmp` and `longjmp` functions that act as non-local gotos.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Common Lisp allows control of what happens when the stack is unwound by using the `unwind-protect` special operator.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] When applying a continuation, the stack is (logically) unwound and then rewound with the stack of the continuation.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] This is not the only way to implement continuations; for example, using multiple, explicit stacks, application of a continuation can simply activate its stack and wind a value to be passed.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] The Scheme programming language allows arbitrary thunks to be executed in specified points on "unwinding" or "rewinding" of the control stack when a continuation is invoked.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] The call stack can sometimes be inspected as the program is running.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Depending on how the program is written and compiled, the information on the stack can be used to determine intermediate values and function call traces.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] This has been used to generate fine-grained automated tests, and in cases like Ruby and Smalltalk, to implement first-class continuations.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] As an example, the GNU Debugger (GDB) implements interactive inspection of the call stack of a running, but paused, C program.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Taking regular-time samples of the call stack can be useful in profiling the performance of programs as, if a subroutine's address appears in the call stack sampling data many times, it is likely to act as a code bottleneck and should be inspected for performance problems.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] One such attack involves filling one buffer with arbitrary executable code, and then overflowing this or some other buffer to overwrite some return address with a value that points directly to the executable code.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] As a result, when the function returns, the computer executes that code.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] This kind of an attack can be blocked with W^X, but similar attacks can succeed even with W^X protection enabled, including the return-to-libc attack or the attacks coming from return-oriented programming.
[src:flame-graphs/call-stack] Various mitigations have been proposed, such as storing arrays in a completely separate location from the return stack, as is the case in the Forth programming language.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] In addition, **Narrative visualization** is a method that uses visual elements such as charts, graphs, maps and the like to convey data or information.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] This approach blends data analysis, storytelling, and visualization to present information through structured narrative flows- *using visuals not just to present statistics, but to tell a story through data*.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Its goal is to help people identify trends, patterns, and relationships in data through a compelling story-driven visual experience.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Emerging technologies like virtual, augmented and mixed reality have the potential to make information visualization more immersive, intuitive, interactive and easily manipulable and thus enhance the user's visual perception and cognition.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Effective data visualization is well-sourced, appropriately contextualized, and presented in a simple, uncluttered manner.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] The underlying data is accurate and up-to-date to ensure insights are reliable.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Graphical items are well-chosen and aesthetically appealing, with shapes, colors and other visual elements used deliberately in a meaningful and non-distracting manner.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] The visuals are accompanied by supporting texts.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Verbal and graphical components complement each other to ensure clear, quick and memorable understanding.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Effective information visualization is aware of the needs and expertise level of the target audience.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Data scientists, analysts and data mining specialists use data visualization to check data quality, find errors, unusual gaps, missing values, clean data, explore the structures and features of data, and assess outputs of data-driven models.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization can be part of *data storytelling*, where they are paired with a narrative structure, to contextualize the analyzed data and communicate insights gained from analyzing it to convince the audience into making a decision or taking action.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization is interdisciplinary, it incorporates principles found in descriptive statistics, visual communication, graphic design, cognitive science and, interactive computer graphics and human-computer interaction.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Since effective visualization requires design skills, statistical skills and computing skills, it is both an art and a science.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Visual analytics combines statistical data analysis, data and information visualization, and human analytical reasoning through interactive visual interfaces to help users reach conclusions, gain actionable insights and make informed decisions which are otherwise difficult for computers to do.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Research into how people read and misread types of visualizations helps to determine what types and features of visualizations are most understandable and effective.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Unintentionally poor or intentionally misleading and deceptive visualizations can function as powerful tools which disseminate misinformation, manipulate public perception and divert public opinion.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Thus data visualization literacy has become an important component of data and information literacy in the information age akin to the roles played by textual, mathematical and visual literacy in the past.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] The field of data and information visualization has emerged "from research in human–computer interaction, computer science, graphics, visual design, psychology, photography and business methods.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] It is increasingly applied as a critical component in scientific research, digital libraries, data mining, financial data analysis, market studies, manufacturing production control, and drug discovery".
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization presumes that "visual representations and interaction techniques take advantage of the human eye's broad bandwidth pathway into the mind to allow users to see, explore, and understand large amounts of information at once.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Data analysis is an indispensable part of all applied research and problem solving in industry.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Among these approaches, information visualization, or visual data analysis, is the most reliant on the cognitive skills of human analysts, and allows the discovery of unstructured actionable insights that are limited only by human imagination and creativity.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] The analyst does not have to learn any sophisticated methods to be able to interpret the visualizations of the data.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Information visualization is also a hypothesis generation scheme, which can be, and is typically followed by more analytical or formal analysis, such as statistical hypothesis testing.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] To communicate information clearly and efficiently, data visualization uses statistical graphics, plots, information graphics and other tools.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Numerical data may be encoded using dots, lines, or bars, to visually communicate a quantitative message.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Effective visualization helps users analyze and reason about data and evidence.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] It makes complex data more accessible, understandable, and usable, but can also be reductive.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Users may have particular analytical tasks, such as making comparisons or understanding causality, and the design principle of the graphic (i.e., showing comparisons or showing causality) follows the task.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Tables are generally used where users will look up a specific measurement, while charts of various types are used to show patterns or relationships in the data for one or more variables.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Data visualization refers to the techniques used to communicate data or information by encoding it as visual objects (e.g., points, lines, or bars) contained in graphics.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] The goal is to communicate information clearly and efficiently to users.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] It is one of the steps in data analysis or data science.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] According to Vitaly Friedman (2008) the "main goal of data visualization is to communicate information clearly and effectively through graphical means.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] It doesn't mean that data visualization needs to look boring to be functional or extremely sophisticated to look beautiful.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] To convey ideas effectively, both aesthetic form and functionality need to go hand in hand, providing insights into a rather sparse and complex data set by communicating its key aspects in a more intuitive way.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Yet designers often fail to achieve a balance between form and function, creating gorgeous data visualizations which fail to serve their main purpose — to communicate information".
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Wattenberg suggested that an ideal visualization should not only communicate clearly, but stimulate viewer engagement and attention.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Data visualization is closely related to information graphics, information visualization, scientific visualization, exploratory data analysis and statistical graphics.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] In the new millennium, data visualization has become an active area of research, teaching and development.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] (2002), it has united scientific and information visualization.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] In the commercial environment data visualization is often referred to as dashboards.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Infographics are another very common form of data visualization.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Edward Tufte has explained that users of information displays are executing particular *analytical tasks* such as making comparisons.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] The *design principle* of the information graphic should support the analytical task.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] As William Cleveland and Robert McGill show, different graphical elements accomplish this more or less effectively.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] For example, dot plots and bar charts outperform pie charts.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] In his 1983 book *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information*, Edward Tufte defines 'graphical displays' and principles for effective graphical display in the following passage: "Excellence in statistical graphics consists of complex ideas communicated with clarity, precision, and efficiency.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] For example, the Minard diagram shows the losses suffered by Napoleon's army in the 1812–1813 period.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Six variables are plotted: the size of the army, its location on a two-dimensional surface (x and y), time, the direction of movement, and temperature.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] The line width illustrates a comparison (size of the army at points in time), while the temperature axis suggests a cause of the change in army size.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] This multivariate display on a two-dimensional surface tells a story that can be grasped immediately while identifying the source data to build credibility.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Not applying these principles may result in misleading graphs, distorting the message, or supporting an erroneous conclusion.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] According to Tufte, chartjunk refers to the extraneous interior decoration of the graphic that does not enhance the message or gratuitous three-dimensional or perspective effects.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Needlessly separating the explanatory key from the image itself, requiring the eye to travel back and forth from the image to the key, is a form of "administrative debris." The ratio of "data to ink" should be maximized, erasing non-data ink where feasible.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] The Congressional Budget Office summarized several best practices for graphical displays in a June 2014 presentation.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] These included: a) Knowing your audience; b) Designing graphics that can stand alone outside the report's context; and c) Designing graphics that communicate the key messages in the report.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] For greatest efficiency and simplicity of design and user experience, this readability is enhanced through the use of bijective mapping in that design of the image elements - where the mapping of representational element to data variable is unique.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Kosara (2007) also identifies the need for a visualisation to be "recognisable as a visualisation and not appear to be something else".
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] He also states that recognisability and readability may not always be required in all types of visualisation e.g.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] "informative art" (which would still meet all three above criteria but might not look like a visualisation) or "artistic visualisation" (which similarly is still based on non-visual data to create an image, but may not be readable or recognisable).
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Ranking: Categorical subdivisions are ranked in ascending or descending order, such as a ranking of sales performance (the *measure*) by sales persons (the *category*, with each sales person a *categorical subdivision*) during a single period.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used to show the comparison across the sales persons.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Part-to-whole: Categorical subdivisions are measured as a ratio to the whole (i.e., a percentage out of 100%).
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] A pie chart or bar chart can show the comparison of ratios, such as the market share represented by competitors in a market.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Deviation: Categorical subdivisions are compared against a reference, such as a comparison of actual vs. budget expenses for several departments of a business for a given time period.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] A bar chart can show comparison of the actual versus the reference amount.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Frequency distribution: Shows the number of observations of a particular variable for given interval, such as the number of years in which the stock market return is between intervals such as 0–10%, 11–20%, etc.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] A histogram, a type of bar chart, may be used for this analysis.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] A boxplot helps visualize key statistics about the distribution, such as median, quartiles, outliers, etc.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Correlation: Comparison between observations represented by two variables (X,Y) to determine if they tend to move in the same or opposite directions.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] For example, plotting unemployment (X) and inflation (Y) for a sample of months.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] A scatter plot is typically used for this message.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Nominal comparison: Comparing categorical subdivisions in no particular order, such as the sales volume by product code.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used for this comparison.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Geographic or geospatial: Comparison of a variable across a map or layout, such as the unemployment rate by state or the number of persons on the various floors of a building.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Analysts reviewing a set of data may consider whether some or all of the messages and graphic types above are applicable to their task and audience.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] The process of trial and error to identify meaningful relationships and messages in the data is part of exploratory data analysis.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] A human can distinguish differences in line length, shape, orientation, distances, and color (hue) readily without significant processing effort; these are referred to as "pre-attentive attributes".
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] For example, it may require significant time and effort ("attentive processing") to identify the number of times the digit "5" appears in a series of numbers; but if that digit is different in size, orientation, or color, instances of the digit can be noted quickly through pre-attentive processing.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Compelling graphics take advantage of pre-attentive processing and attributes and the relative strength of these attributes.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] For example, since humans can more easily process differences in line length than surface area, it may be more effective to use a bar chart (which takes advantage of line length to show comparison) rather than pie charts (which use surface area to show comparison).
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Almost all data visualizations are created for human consumption.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Knowledge of human perception and cognition is necessary when designing intuitive visualizations.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Cognition refers to processes in human beings like perception, attention, learning, memory, thought, concept formation, reading, and problem solving.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Human visual processing is efficient in detecting changes and making comparisons between quantities, sizes, shapes and variations in lightness.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] When properties of symbolic data are mapped to visual properties, humans can browse through large amounts of data efficiently.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] It is estimated that 2/3 of the brain's neurons can be involved in visual processing.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Proper visualization provides a different approach to show potential connections, relationships, etc. which are not as obvious in non-visualized quantitative data.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Visualization can become a means of data exploration.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Studies have shown individuals used on average 19% less cognitive resources, and 4.5% better able to recall details when comparing data visualization with text.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] There is no comprehensive history of data visualization.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] There are no accounts that span the entire development of visual thinking and visual representation of data, and which collate the contributions of disparate disciplines.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Michael Friendly and Daniel Denis of York University are engaged in a project that attempts to provide a comprehensive history of visualization.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Data visualization is not a modern development.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Since prehistory, stellar data, or information such as location of stars were visualized on the walls of caves (such as those found in Lascaux Cave in Southern France) since the Pleistocene era.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Physical artefacts such as Mesopotamian clay tokens (5500 BC), Inca quipus (2600 BC) and Marshall Islands stick charts (n.d.) can also be considered as visualizing quantitative information.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] The first documented data visualization can be tracked back to 1160 B.C. with the Turin Papyrus Map which accurately illustrates the distribution of geological resources and provides information about quarrying of those resources.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Such maps can be categorized as thematic cartography, which is a type of data visualization that presents and communicates specific data and information through a geographical illustration designed to show a particular theme connected with a specific geographic area.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Earliest documented forms of data visualization were various thematic maps from different cultures and ideograms and hieroglyphs that provided and allowed interpretation of information illustrated.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] For example, Linear B tablets of Mycenae provided a visualization of information regarding Late Bronze Age era trades in the Mediterranean.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] The idea of coordinates was used by ancient Egyptian surveyors in laying out towns, earthly and heavenly positions were located by something akin to latitude and longitude at least by 200 BC, and the map projection of a spherical Earth into latitude and longitude by Claudius Ptolemy [c.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] 165] in Alexandria would serve as reference standards until the 14th century.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] The invention of paper and parchment allowed further development of visualizations.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] One graph from the 10th or possibly 11th century is an illustration of planetary movements, used in an appendix of a textbook in monastery schools.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] The graph apparently was meant to represent a plot of the inclinations of the planetary orbits as a function of the time.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] For this purpose, the zone of the zodiac was represented on a plane with a horizontal line divided into thirty parts as the time or longitudinal axis.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] The vertical axis designates the width of the zodiac.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] The horizontal scale appears to have been chosen for each planet individually for the periods cannot be reconciled.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] The accompanying text refers only to the amplitudes.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] The curves are apparently not related in time.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] By the 16th century, techniques and instruments for precise observation and measurement of physical quantities, and geographic and celestial position were well-developed (for example, a "wall quadrant" constructed by Tycho Brahe [1546–1601], covering an entire wall in his observatory).
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Particularly important were the development of triangulation and other methods to determine mapping locations accurately.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Very early, the measure of time led scholars to develop innovative way of visualizing the data (e.g.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Lorenz Codomann in 1596, Johannes Temporarius in 1596).
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Mathematicians René Descartes and Pierre de Fermat developed analytic geometry and two-dimensional coordinate system which heavily influenced the practical methods of displaying and calculating values.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Fermat and Blaise Pascal's work on statistics and probability theory laid the groundwork for what we now conceptualize as data.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] These developments helped William Playfair, who saw potential for graphical communication of quantitative data, to generate and develop graphical methods of statistics.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] In 1786, Playfair published the first presentation graphics.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] In the second half of the 20th century, Jacques Bertin used quantitative graphs to represent information "intuitively, clearly, accurately, and efficiently".
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] John Tukey and Edward Tufte pushed the bounds of data visualization; Tukey with his new statistical approach of exploratory data analysis and Tufte with his book "The Visual Display of Quantitative Information" paved the way for refining data visualization techniques for more than statisticians.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] With the progression of technology came the progression of data visualization; starting with hand-drawn visualizations and evolving into more technical applications – including interactive designs leading to software visualization.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] The modern study of visualization started with computer graphics, which "has from its beginning been used to study scientific problems.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] However, in its early days the lack of graphics power often limited its usefulness.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] The recent emphasis on visualization started in 1987 with the special issue of Computer Graphics on Visualization in *Scientific Computing*.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Since then there have been several conferences and workshops, co-sponsored by the IEEE Computer Society and ACM SIGGRAPH".
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] They have been devoted to the general topics of data visualization, information visualization and scientific visualization, and more specific areas such as volume visualization.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Programs like SAS, SOFA, R, Minitab, Cornerstone and more allow for data visualization in the field of statistics.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Other data visualization applications, more focused and unique to individuals, programming languages such as D3, Python (through matplotlib, seaborn) and JavaScript and Java(through JavaFX) help to make the visualization of quantitative data a possibility.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Private schools have also developed programs to meet the demand for learning data visualization and associated programming libraries, including free programs like The Data Incubator or paid programs like General Assembly.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Beginning with the symposium "Data to Discovery" in 2013, ArtCenter College of Design, Caltech and JPL in Pasadena have run an annual program on interactive data visualization.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] The program asks: How can interactive data visualization help scientists and engineers explore their data more effectively?
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] How can computing, design, and design thinking help maximize research results?
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] What methodologies are most effective for leveraging knowledge from these fields?
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] In recent years, with the increasing popularity of games, data and information visualization has been gradually applied in the gaming industry through the use of analytical tools to assess player statistics and game performance, which are visualized in the form of health points, maps, and diagrams.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] The data is then collected and stored by developers.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] The implementation of these tools in gaming assists developers in improving user experience and in the development and updating of newer games.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Data visualization involves specific terminology, some of which is derived from statistics.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] The distinction between quantitative and categorical variables is important because the two types require different methods of visualization.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Two primary types of information displays are tables and graphs.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Eppler and Lengler have developed the "Periodic Table of Visualization Methods," an interactive chart displaying various data visualization methods.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] It includes six types of data visualization methods: data, information, concept, strategy, metaphor and compound.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Interactive data visualization has been a pursuit of statisticians since the late 1960s.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Examples of the developments can be found on the American Statistical Association video lending library.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] There are different approaches on the scope of data visualization.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] One common focus is on information presentation, such as Friedman (2008).
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Friendly (2008) presumes two main parts of data visualization: statistical graphics, and thematic cartography.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] All these subjects are closely related to graphic design and information representation.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Within The Harvard Business Review, Scott Berinato developed a framework to approach data visualisation.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] To start thinking visually, users must consider two questions; 1) What you have and 2) what you're doing.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] The first step is identifying what data you want visualised.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] It is data-driven like profit over the past ten years or a conceptual idea like how a specific organisation is structured.
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Once this question is answered one can then focus on whether they are trying to communicate information (declarative visualisation) or trying to figure something out (exploratory visualisation).
[src:flame-graphs/data-and-information-visualization-p01] Scott Berinato combines these questions to give four types of visual communication that each have their own goals.
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] This is the official website for flame graphs: a visualization of hierarchical data that I created to visualize stack traces of profiled software so that the most frequent code-paths can be identified quickly and accurately.
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] They can be generated using my open source programs on github.com/brendangregg/FlameGraph which create interactive SVGs.
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] There are now over 100 other implementations, many open source (see the Updates section) and they are also now available in most commercial profilers.
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] My colleague on the Netflix performance engineering team, Martin Spier, created a more interactive d3 version, also widely used: d3-flame-graph.
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] The example on the right is a portion of a CPU flame graph, showing MySQL codepaths that are consuming CPU cycles, and by how much.
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] Flame graphs can also be used for any hierarchical data.
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] E.g., file system contents (see instructions; comparisons with treemaps and sunbursts).
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] To generate them for custom time ranges for the study of variation, perturbations, and periodic activity, see FlameScope.
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] On this page: Summary, OSes, Presentation, Variations, Origin, Updates.
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] The x-axis shows the stack profile population, sorted alphabetically (it is not the passage of time), and the y-axis shows stack depth, counting from zero at the bottom.
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] Each rectangle represents a stack frame.
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] The wider a frame is is, the more often it was present in the stacks.
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] The top edge shows what is on-CPU, and beneath it is its ancestry.
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] Original flame graphs use random colors to help visually differentiate adjacent frames.
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] Variations include inverting the y-axis (an "icicle graph"), changing the hue to indicate code type, and using a color spectrum to convey an additional dimension.
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] Flame graphs are both a static and dynamic visualization.
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] As a static visualization, a flame graph can be saved as an image, included in print (books), and will still convey the "big picture" as only the most frequent frames have enough width for labels.
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] This visualization is fully explained in my ACMQ article The Flame Graph, also published in Communications of the ACM, Vol.
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] Also see my CPU Flame Graphs page, and the presentation below.
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] Once you have a profiler that can generate meaningful stacks, converting them into a flame graph is usually the easy step.
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] There are also numerous profiling products and companies that now support flame graphs.
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] I invented flame graphs when working on a MySQL performance issue and needed to understand CPU usage quickly and in depth.
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] The regular profilers/tracers had produced walls of text, so I was exploring visualizations.
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] I first traced CPU function calls and visualized it using Neelakanth Nadgir's time-ordered visualization for callstacks, which itself was inspired by Roch Bourbonnais's CallStackAnalyzer and Jan Boerhout's vftrace.
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] These look similar to flame graphs, but have the passage of time on the x-axis.
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] But there were two problems: the overhead of function tracing was too high, perturbing the target, and the final visualization was too dense to read when spanning multiple seconds.
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] I switched to timed sampling (profiling) to solve the overhead problem, but since the function flow is no longer known (sampling has gaps) I ditched time on the x-axis and reordered samples to maximize frame merging.
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] It worked, the final visualization was much more readable.
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] Neelakanth and Roch's visualizations used completely random colors to differentiate frames.
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] I thought it looked nicer to narrow the color palette, and picked just warm colors initially as it explained why the CPUs were "hot" (busy).
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] Since it resembled flames, it quickly became known as flame graphs.
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] I described more detail of the original performance problem that led to flame graphs in my ACMQ/CACM article (link above).
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] The flame graph visualization is really an adjacency diagram with an inverted icicle layout, which I used to visualize profiled stack traces.
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] Thanks to everyone who has written about flame graphs, developed them further, and shared their results!
[src:flame-graphs/flamegraphs] I'll update this page from time to time with more news.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] In software engineering, **profiling** (**program profiling**, **software profiling**) is a form of dynamic program analysis that measures, for example, the space (memory) or time complexity of a program, the usage of particular instructions, or the frequency and duration of function calls.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] Most commonly, profiling information serves to aid program optimization, and more specifically, performance engineering.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] Profiling is achieved by instrumenting either the program source code or its binary executable form using a tool called a *profiler* (or *code profiler*).
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] Profilers may use a number of different techniques, such as event-based, statistical, instrumented, and simulation methods.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] Profilers use a wide variety of techniques to collect data, including hardware interrupts, code instrumentation, instruction set simulation, operating system hooks, and performance counters.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] Summary profile information is often shown annotated against the source code statements where the events occur, so the size of measurement data is linear to the code size of the program.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] For sequential programs, a summary profile is usually sufficient, but performance problems in parallel programs (waiting for messages or synchronization issues) often depend on the time relationship of events, thus requiring a full trace to get an understanding of what is happening.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] A trace may therefore be initiated at one point in a program and terminated at another point to limit the output.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] This provides the opportunity to switch a trace on or off at any desired point during execution in addition to viewing on-going metrics about the (still executing) program.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] It also provides the opportunity to suspend asynchronous processes at critical points to examine interactions with other parallel processes in more detail.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] A profiler can be applied to an individual method or at the scale of a module or program, to identify performance bottlenecks by making long-running code obvious.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] A profiler can be used to understand code from a timing point of view, with the objective of optimizing it to handle various runtime conditions or various loads.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] Profiling results can be ingested by a compiler that provides profile-guided optimization.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] Profiling results can be used to guide the design and optimization of an individual algorithm; the Krauss matching wildcards algorithm is an example.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] Profilers are built into some application performance management systems that aggregate profiling data to provide insight into transaction workloads in distributed applications.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] Performance-analysis tools existed on IBM/360 and IBM/370 platforms from the early 1970s, usually based on timer interrupts which recorded the program status word (PSW) at set timer-intervals to detect "hot spots" in executing code.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] This was an early example of sampling (see below).
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] In early 1974 instruction-set simulators permitted full trace and other performance-monitoring features.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] Profiler-driven program analysis on Unix dates back to 1973, when Unix systems included a basic tool, `prof`, which listed each function and how much of program execution time it used.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] In 1982 `gprof` extended the concept to a complete call graph analysis.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] In 1994, Amitabh Srivastava and Alan Eustace of Digital Equipment Corporation published a paper describing ATOM (Analysis Tools with OM).
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] The ATOM platform converts a program into its own profiler: at compile time, it inserts code into the program to be analyzed.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] That inserted code outputs analysis data.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] This technique - modifying a program to analyze itself - is known as "instrumentation".
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] In 2004 both the `gprof` and ATOM papers appeared on the list of the 50 most influential PLDI papers for the 20-year period ending in 1999.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] Flat profilers compute the average call times, from the calls, and do not break down the call times based on the callee or the context.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] Call graph profilers show the call times, and frequencies of the functions, and also the call-chains involved based on the callee.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] In some tools full context is not preserved.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] Input-sensitive profilers add a further dimension to flat or call-graph profilers by relating performance measures to features of the input workloads, such as input size or input values.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] They generate charts that characterize how an application's performance scales as a function of its input.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] Profilers, which are also programs themselves, analyze target programs by collecting information on the target program's execution.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] Based on their data granularity, which depends upon how profilers collect information, they are classified as *event-based* or *statistical* profilers.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] Profilers interrupt program execution to collect information.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] Those interrupts can limit time measurement resolution, which implies that timing results should be taken with a grain of salt.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] Basic block profilers report a number of machine clock cycles devoted to executing each line of code, or timing based on adding those together; the timings reported per basic block may not reflect a difference between cache hits and misses.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] A sampling profiler probes the target program's call stack at regular intervals using operating system interrupts.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] Sampling profiles are typically less numerically accurate and specific, providing only a statistical approximation, but allow the target program to run at near full speed.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] "The actual amount of error is usually more than one sampling period.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] In practice, sampling profilers can often provide a more accurate picture of the target program's execution than other approaches, as they are not as intrusive to the target program and thus don't have as many side effects (such as on memory caches or instruction decoding pipelines).
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] Also since they don't create much overhead, they can detect issues that would otherwise be hidden.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] They are also relatively immune to over-evaluating the cost of small, frequently called routines or 'tight' loops.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] They can show the relative amount of time spent in user mode versus interruptible kernel mode such as system call processing.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] Unfortunately, running kernel code to handle the interrupts incurs a minor loss of CPU cycles from the target program, diverts cache usage, and cannot distinguish the various tasks occurring in uninterruptible kernel code (microsecond-range activity) from user code.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] Dedicated hardware can do better: ARM Cortex-M3 and some recent MIPS processors' JTAG interfaces have a PCSAMPLE register, which samples the program counter in a truly undetectable manner, allowing non-intrusive collection of a flat profile.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] Some commonly used statistical profilers for Java/managed code are SmartBear Software's AQtime and Microsoft's CLR Profiler.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] Those profilers also support native code profiling, along with Apple Inc.'s Shark (OSX), OProfile (Linux), Intel VTune and Parallel Amplifier (part of Intel Parallel Studio), and Oracle Performance Analyzer, among others.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] This technique effectively adds instructions to the target program to collect the required information.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] Note that instrumenting a program can cause performance changes, and may in some cases lead to inaccurate results and/or heisenbugs.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] The effect will depend on what information is being collected, on the level of timing details reported, and on whether basic block profiling is used in conjunction with instrumentation.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] For example, adding code to count every procedure/routine call will probably have less effect than counting how many times each statement is obeyed.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] A few computers have special hardware to collect information; in this case the impact on the program is minimal.
[src:flame-graphs/profiling-computer-programming] Instrumentation is key to determining the level of control and amount of time resolution available to the profilers.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] In computer science, **program optimization**, **code optimization**, or **software optimization** is the process of modifying a software system to make some aspect of it work more efficiently or use fewer resources.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] In general, a computer program may be optimized so that it executes more rapidly, or to make it capable of operating with less memory storage or other resources, or draw less power.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Although the term "optimization" is derived from "optimum", achieving a truly optimal system is rare in practice, which is referred to as superoptimization.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Optimization typically focuses on improving a system with respect to a specific quality metric rather than making it universally optimal.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] This often leads to trade-offs, where enhancing one metric may come at the expense of another.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] One frequently cited example is the space–time tradeoff, where reducing a program’s execution time can increase its memory consumption.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Conversely, in scenarios where memory is limited, engineers might prioritize a slower algorithm to conserve space.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] There is rarely a single design that can excel in all situations, requiring programmers to prioritize attributes most relevant to the application at hand.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Metrics for software include throughput, latency, volatile memory usage, persistent storage, internet usage, energy consumption, and hardware wear and tear.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Furthermore, achieving absolute optimization often demands disproportionate effort relative to the benefits gained.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Consequently, optimization processes usually slow once sufficient improvements are achieved.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Fortunately, significant gains often occur early in the optimization process, making it practical to stop before reaching diminishing returns.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Optimization can occur at a number of levels.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Typically the higher levels have greater impact, and are harder to change later on in a project, requiring significant changes or a complete rewrite if they need to be changed.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Thus optimization can typically proceed via refinement from higher to lower, with initial gains being larger and achieved with less work, and later gains being smaller and requiring more work.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] However, in some cases overall performance depends on performance of very low-level portions of a program, and small changes at a late stage or early consideration of low-level details can have outsized impact.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Typically some consideration is given to efficiency throughout a project – though this varies significantly – but major optimization is often considered a refinement to be done late, if ever.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] On longer-running projects there are typically cycles of optimization, where improving one area reveals limitations in another, and these are typically curtailed when performance is acceptable or gains become too small or costly.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Best practices for optimization during iterative development cycles include continuous monitoring for performance issues coupled with regular performance testing.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] The degree to which performance changes between prototype and production system, and how amenable it is to optimization, can be a significant source of uncertainty and risk.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] At the highest level, the design may be optimized to make best use of the available resources, given goals, constraints, and expected use/load.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] The architectural design of a system overwhelmingly affects its performance.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] For example, a system that is network latency-bound (where network latency is the main constraint on overall performance) would be optimized to minimize network trips, ideally making a single request (or no requests, as in a push protocol) rather than multiple roundtrips.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Choice of platform and programming language occur at this level, and changing them frequently requires a complete rewrite, though a modular system may allow rewrite of only some component – for example, for a Python program one may rewrite performance-critical sections in C.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] In a distributed system, choice of architecture (client-server, peer-to-peer, etc.) occurs at the design level, and may be difficult to change, particularly if all components cannot be replaced in sync (e.g., old clients).
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Given an overall design, a good choice of efficient algorithms and data structures, and efficient implementation of these algorithms and data structures comes next.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] After design, the choice of algorithms and data structures affects efficiency more than any other aspect of the program.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Changes in data structures mapped to a database may require schema migration and other complex software or infrastructure changes.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] For algorithms, this primarily consists of ensuring that algorithms are constant O(1), logarithmic O(log *n*), linear O(*n*), or in some cases log-linear O(*n* log *n*) in the input (both in space and time).
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Algorithms with quadratic complexity O(*n*2) fail to scale, and even linear algorithms cause problems if repeatedly called, and are typically replaced with constant or logarithmic if possible.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Beyond asymptotic order of growth, the constant factors matter: an asymptotically slower algorithm may be faster or smaller (because simpler) than an asymptotically faster algorithm when they are both faced with small input, which may be the case that occurs in reality.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Often a hybrid algorithm will provide the best performance, due to this tradeoff changing with size.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] A general technique to improve performance is to avoid work.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] A good example is the use of a fast path for common cases, improving performance by avoiding unnecessary work.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] For example, using a simple text layout algorithm for Latin text, only switching to a complex layout algorithm for complex scripts, such as Devanagari.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Another important technique is caching, particularly memoization, which avoids redundant computations.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Because of the importance of caching, there are often many levels of caching in a system, which can cause problems from memory use, and correctness issues from stale caches.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Beyond general algorithms and their implementation on an abstract machine, concrete source code level choices can make a significant difference.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] For example, on early C compilers, `while (true)` was slower than `for (;;)` for an unconditional loop, because `while (true)` evaluated `true` and then had a conditional jump which tested if it was true, while `for (;;)` had an unconditional jump.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Some optimizations (such as this one) can nowadays be performed by optimizing compilers.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] This depends on the source language, the target machine language, and the compiler, and can be both difficult to understand or predict and changes over time; this is a key place where understanding of compilers and machine code can improve performance.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Loop-invariant code motion and return value optimization are examples of optimizations that reduce the need for auxiliary variables and can even result in faster performance by avoiding round-about optimizations.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Source-based software distribution systems such as BSD's Ports and Gentoo's Portage can take advantage of this form of optimization.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Use of an optimizing compiler with optimizations enabled tends to ensure that the executable program is optimized at least as much as the compiler can reasonable perform.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] See Optimizing compiler for more details.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] At the lowest level, writing code using an assembly language, designed for a particular hardware platform can produce the most efficient and compact code if the programmer takes advantage of the full repertoire of machine instructions.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Many operating systems used on embedded systems have been traditionally written in assembler code for this reason.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Programs (other than very small programs) are seldom written from start to finish in assembly due to the time and cost involved.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Most are compiled down from a high level language to assembly and hand optimized from there.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] When efficiency and size are less important large parts may be written in a high-level language.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] With more modern optimizing compilers and the greater complexity of recent CPUs, it is harder to write more efficient code than what the compiler generates, and few projects need this "ultimate" optimization step.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Much of the code written today is intended to run on as many machines as possible.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] As a consequence, programmers and compilers don't always take advantage of the more efficient instructions provided by newer CPUs or quirks of older models.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Additionally, assembly code tuned for a particular processor without using such instructions might still be suboptimal on a different processor, expecting a different tuning of the code.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Typically today rather than writing in assembly language, programmers will use a disassembler to analyze the output of a compiler and change the high-level source code so that it can be compiled more efficiently, or understand why it is inefficient.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Just-in-time compilers can produce customized machine code based on run-time data, at the cost of compilation overhead.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] This technique dates to the earliest regular expression engines, and has become widespread with Java HotSpot and V8 for JavaScript.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] In some cases adaptive optimization may be able to perform run time optimization exceeding the capability of static compilers by dynamically adjusting parameters according to the actual input or other factors.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Profile-guided optimization is an ahead-of-time (AOT) compilation optimization technique based on run time profiles, and is similar to a static "average case" analog of the dynamic technique of adaptive optimization.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Self-modifying code can alter itself in response to run time conditions in order to optimize code; this was more common in assembly language programs.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Some CPU designs can perform some optimizations at run time.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Some examples include out-of-order execution, speculative execution, instruction pipelines, and branch predictors.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Compilers can help the program take advantage of these CPU features, for example through instruction scheduling.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Code optimization can be also broadly categorized as platform-dependent and platform-independent techniques.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] While the latter ones are effective on most or all platforms, platform-dependent techniques use specific properties of one platform, or rely on parameters depending on the single platform or even on the single processor.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Writing or producing different versions of the same code for different processors might therefore be needed.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] For instance, in the case of compile-level optimization, platform-independent techniques are generic techniques (such as loop unrolling, reduction in function calls, memory efficient routines, reduction in conditions, etc.), that impact most CPU architectures in a similar way.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] A great example of platform-independent optimization has been shown with inner for loop, where it was observed that a loop with an inner for loop performs more computations per unit time than a loop without it or one with an inner while loop.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Generally, these serve to reduce the total instruction path length required to complete the program and/or reduce total memory usage during the process.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Computational tasks can be performed in several different ways with varying efficiency.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] A more efficient version with equivalent functionality is known as a strength reduction.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] The optimization, sometimes performed automatically by an optimizing compiler, is to select a method (algorithm) that is more computationally efficient, while retaining the same functionality.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] See algorithmic efficiency for a discussion of some of these techniques.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] However, a significant improvement in performance can often be achieved by removing extraneous functionality.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Optimization is not always an obvious or intuitive process.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] In the example above, the "optimized" version might actually be slower than the original version if *N* were sufficiently small and the particular hardware happens to be much faster at performing addition and looping operations than multiplication and division.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] In some cases, however, optimization relies on using more elaborate algorithms, making use of "special cases" and special "tricks" and performing complex trade-offs.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] A "fully optimized" program might be more difficult to comprehend and hence may contain more faults than unoptimized versions.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Beyond eliminating obvious antipatterns, some code level optimizations decrease maintainability.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Optimization will generally focus on improving just one or two aspects of performance: execution time, memory usage, disk space, bandwidth, power consumption or some other resource.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] This will usually require a trade-off – where one factor is optimized at the expense of others.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] For example, increasing the size of cache improves run time performance, but also increases the memory consumption.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Other common trade-offs include code clarity and conciseness.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] There are instances where the programmer performing the optimization must decide to make the software better for some operations but at the cost of making other operations less efficient.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] These trade-offs may sometimes be of a non-technical nature – such as when a competitor has published a benchmark result that must be beaten in order to improve commercial success but comes perhaps with the burden of making normal usage of the software less efficient.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Such changes are sometimes jokingly referred to as *pessimizations*.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Optimization may include finding a bottleneck in a system – a component that is the limiting factor on performance.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] In terms of code, this will often be a hot spot – a critical part of the code that is the primary consumer of the needed resource – though it can be another factor, such as I/O latency or network bandwidth.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] In computer science, resource consumption often follows a form of power law distribution, and the Pareto principle can be applied to resource optimization by observing that 80% of the resources are typically used by 20% of the operations.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] In software engineering, it is often a better approximation that 90% of the execution time of a computer program is spent executing 10% of the code (known as the 90/10 law in this context).
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] A performance profiler can be used to narrow down decisions about which functionality fits which conditions.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Performance profiling therefore provides not only bottleneck detection but rather a variety of methods for optimization guidance.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Empirical algorithmics is the practice of using empirical methods, typically performance profiling, to study the behavior of algorithms, for developer understanding that may lead to human-planned optimizations.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Profile-guided optimization is the machine-driven use of profiling data as input to an optimizing compiler or interpreter.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Some programming languages are associated with tools for profile-guided optimization.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Some performance profiling methods emphasize enhancements based on cache utilization.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Other benefits of performance profiling may include improved resource management and an enhanced user experience.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] In some cases, adding more memory can help to make a program run faster.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] For example, a filtering program will commonly read each line and filter and output that line immediately.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] This only uses enough memory for one line, but performance is typically poor, due to the latency of each disk read.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Caching the result is similarly effective, though also requiring larger memory use.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Typically, optimization involves choosing the best overall algorithms and data structures.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Frequently, algorithmic improvements can cause performance improvements of several orders of magnitude instead of micro-optimizations, which rarely improve performance by more than a few percent.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] If one waits to optimize until the end of the development cycle, then changing the algorithm could require a significant rewrite.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Frequently, micro-optimization can reduce readability and complicate programs or systems.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] That can make programs more difficult to maintain and debug.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] "Premature optimization" is often used as a rallying cry against all optimization in all situations for all purposes.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Frequently, Clean Code causes code to be more complicated than simpler more efficient code.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] When deciding what to optimize, Amdahl's Law should be used to proritize parts based on the actual time spent in a certain part, which is not always clear from looking at the code without a performance analysis.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] In practice, it is often necessary to keep performance goals in mind when first designing software, yet programmers must balance various tradeoffs.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Development cost is significant, and hardware is fast.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Modern compilers are efficient enough that the intended performance increases sometimes fail to materialize.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Since compilers perform many automatic optimizations, some optimizations may yield an identical executable.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Also, sometimes hardware may reduce the impact of micro-optimization.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] For example, hardware may cache data that is cached at a software level.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Optimization during code development using macros takes on different forms in different languages.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] In some procedural languages, such as C and C++, macros are implemented using token substitution.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Nowadays, inline functions can be used as a type safe alternative in many cases.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] In both cases, the inlined function body can then undergo further compile-time optimizations by the compiler, including constant folding, which may move some computations to compile time.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] In many functional programming languages, macros are implemented using parse-time substitution of parse trees/abstract syntax trees, which it is claimed makes them safer to use.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Since in many cases interpretation is used, that is one way to ensure that such computations are only performed at parse-time, and sometimes the only way.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Lisp originated this style of macro, and such macros are often called "Lisp-like macros".
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] A similar effect can be achieved by using template metaprogramming in C++.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] In both cases, work is moved to compile-time.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Additionally, C macros do not directly support recursion or iteration, so are not Turing complete.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] As with any optimization, however, it is often difficult to predict where such tools will have the most impact before a project is complete.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Optimization can be automated by compilers or performed by programmers.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Gains are usually limited for local optimization, and larger for global optimizations.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Usually, the most powerful optimization is to find a superior algorithm.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Optimizing a whole system is usually undertaken by programmers because it is too complex for automated optimizers.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] In this situation, programmers or system administrators explicitly change code so that the overall system performs better.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Although it can produce better efficiency, it is far more expensive than automated optimizations.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Since many parameters influence the program performance, the program optimization space is large.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Meta-heuristics and machine learning are used to address the complexity of program optimization.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Use a profiler (or performance analyzer) to find the sections of the program that are taking the most resources – the *bottleneck*.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Programmers sometimes believe they have a clear idea of where the bottleneck is, but intuition is frequently wrong.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Optimizing an unimportant piece of code will typically do little to help the overall performance.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] When the bottleneck is localized, optimization usually starts with a rethinking of the algorithm used in the program.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] More often than not, a particular algorithm can be specifically tailored to a particular problem, yielding better performance than a generic algorithm.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] For example, the task of sorting a huge list of items is usually done with a quicksort routine, which is one of the most efficient generic algorithms.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] But if some characteristic of the items is exploitable (for example, they are already arranged in some particular order), a different method can be used, or even a custom-made sort routine.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] After the programmer is reasonably sure that the best algorithm is selected, code optimization can start.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Loops can be unrolled (for lower loop overhead, although this can often lead to *lower* speed if it overloads the CPU cache), data types as small as possible can be used, integer arithmetic can be used instead of floating-point, and so on.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Performance bottlenecks can be due to language limitations rather than algorithms or data structures used in the program.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Sometimes, a critical part of the program can be re-written in a different programming language that gives more direct access to the underlying machine.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] For example, it is common for very high-level languages like Python to have modules written in C for greater speed.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Programs already written in C can have modules written in assembly.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Programs written in D can use the inline assembler.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Rewriting sections "pays off" in these circumstances because of a general "rule of thumb" known as the 90/10 law, which states that 90% of the time is spent in 10% of the code, and only 10% of the time in the remaining 90% of the code.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] So, putting intellectual effort into optimizing just a small part of the program can have a huge effect on the overall speed – if the correct part(s) can be located.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Manual optimization sometimes has the side effect of undermining readability.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Thus code optimizations should be carefully documented (preferably using in-line comments), and their effect on future development evaluated.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] The program that performs an automated optimization is called an **optimizer**.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Most optimizers are embedded in compilers and operate during compilation.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Optimizers can often tailor the generated code to specific processors.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Today, automated optimizations are almost exclusively limited to compiler optimization.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] However, because compiler optimizations are usually limited to a fixed set of rather general optimizations, there is considerable demand for optimizers which can accept descriptions of problem and language-specific optimizations, allowing an engineer to specify custom optimizations.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Tools that accept descriptions of optimizations are called program transformation systems and are beginning to be applied to real software systems such as C++.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Some high-level languages (Eiffel, Esterel) optimize their programs by using an intermediate language.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Grid computing or distributed computing aims to optimize the whole system, by moving tasks from computers with high usage to computers with idle time.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Sometimes, the time taken to undertake optimization therein itself may be an issue.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Optimizing existing code usually does not add new features, and worse, it might add new bugs in previously working code (as any change might).
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Because manually optimized code might sometimes have less "readability" than unoptimized code, optimization might impact maintainability of it as well.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Optimization comes at a price and it is important to be sure that the investment is worthwhile.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] An automatic optimizer (or optimizing compiler, a program that performs code optimization) may itself have to be optimized, either to further improve the efficiency of its target programs or else speed up its own operation.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] A compilation performed with optimization "turned on" usually takes longer, although this is usually only a problem when programs are quite large.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] In particular, for just-in-time compilers the performance of the run time compile component, executing together with its target code, is the key to improving overall execution speed.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Sometimes, "optimizations" may hurt performance.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Concurrency and parallelism cause significant overhead performance cost and possibly increased energy usage.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Keep in mind that C code rarely uses explicit multiprocessing, yet it typically runs faster than any other programming language.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Disk caching, paging, and swapping often cause significant increases to energy usage and hardware wear and tear.
[src:flame-graphs/program-optimization] Running processes in the background to improve startup time slows down all other processes.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] In computing, a **stack trace** (also called **stack backtrace** or **stack traceback**) is a report of the active stack frames at a certain point in time during the execution of a program.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] When a program is run, memory is often dynamically allocated in two places: the stack and the heap.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] Memory is continuously allocated on a stack but not on a heap.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] Stack also refers to a programming construct, thus to differentiate it, this stack is referred to as the program's **function call stack**.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] Technically, once a block of memory has been allocated on the stack, it cannot be easily removed as there can be other blocks of memory that were allocated after it.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] Each time a function is called in a program, a block of memory called an **activation record** is allocated on top of the call stack.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] Generally, the activation record stores the function's arguments and local variables.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] What exactly it contains and how it's laid out is determined by the calling convention.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] Programmers commonly use stack tracing during interactive and post-mortem debugging.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] End-users may see a stack trace displayed as part of an error message, which the user can then report to a programmer.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] A stack trace allows tracking the sequence of nested functions called - up to the point where the stack trace is generated.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] In a post-mortem scenario this extends up to the function where the failure occurred (but was not necessarily caused).
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] Sibling calls do not appear in a stack trace.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] Many programming languages, including Java and C#, have built-in support for retrieving the current stack trace via system calls.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] Before `std::stacktrace` was added in standard library as a container for `std::stacktrace_entry`, pre-C++23 has no built-in support for doing this, but C++ users can retrieve stack traces with (for example) the stacktrace library.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] In JavaScript, exceptions hold a `stack` property that contain the stack from the place where it was thrown.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] As an example, the following Python program contains an error.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] Running the program under the standard Python interpreter produces the following error message.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] The stack trace shows where the error occurs, namely in the `c` function.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] It also shows that the `c` function was called by `b`, which was called by `a`, which was in turn called by the code on line 16 (the last line) of the program.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] The activation records for each of these three functions would be arranged in a stack such that the `a` function would occupy the bottom of the stack and the `c` function would occupy the top of the stack.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] The exception lists functions in descending order, so the most-inner call is first.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] Java also allows retrieving the current stack trace using `java.lang.Thread::getStackTrace()`, or displaying the stack trace at an error using `java.lang.Throwable::printStackTrace()`.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] A stack trace in Java is represented as `java.lang.StackTraceElement[]`, an array.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] C does not have native support for obtaining stack traces, but libraries such as glibc provide this functionality.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] In C and C++, some compiler optimizations may interfere with the call stack information that can be recovered at runtime.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] For instance, inlining can cause missing stack frames, tail call optimizations can replace one stack frame with another, and frame pointer elimination can prevent call stack analysis tools from correctly interpreting the contents of the call stack.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] For example, glibc's `backtrace()` function returns an output with the program function and memory address.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] Prior to C++23, no mechanisms in C++ existed to obtain stack traces, but third-party libraries like *Boost.Stacktrace* offered stack traces.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] C# offers a `System.Diagnostics.StackTrace` class.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] Functions that use the panic macro are "unrecoverable" and the current thread will become poisoned experiencing stack unwinding.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] Functions that return a `std::result::Result` are "recoverable" and can be handled gracefully.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] However, recoverable errors cannot generate a stack trace as they are manually added and not a result of a runtime error.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] As of June 2021, Rust has experimental support for stack traces on unrecoverable errors.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] Rust supports printing to stderr when a thread panics, but it must be enabled by setting the `RUST_BACKTRACE` environment variable.
[src:flame-graphs/stack-trace] When enabled, such backtraces look similar to below, with the most recent call first.
